In this striking tempera on weave, Roy presents a monumental figure of a woman cradling the infant Ganesh, her presence dominating the composition. The image is meticulously constructed from small squares, reflecting Roy's distinctive approach to form and structure. Three decorative borders frame the central figure, creating a rhythmic containment that enhances the work's visual harmony. The painting is imbued with the artist's signature motifs, simplified, flattened forms, bold outlines, and vibrant, earthy colours evoking both folk traditions and a timeless, devotional aura. Through this work, Roy merges folk aesthetics with a modernist sensibility, celebrating maternal care, divinity, and the enduring power of Indian visual culture.

