Husain made a series of lithographs titled 'Tribute to Mother Theresa,' shortly after she was awarded the Nobel Peace Prize in 1979, for her work among the sick and impoverished in Calcutta. These early prints were mostly in white, grey, brown and black, although her symbolic blue and white sari was a constant feature. Her face was never shown and was replaced by a black void. This was done deliberately by Husain as he thought her to be symbolic of all mothers, and therefore ought to not be identified with just one human being.

